  "prompt": "What is the nature of a photon? Is it a particle or a wave?",
  "response": "The nature of a photon is both wave-like and particle-like, embodying the principle of wave-particle duality from quantum mechanics. This means photons can exhibit characteristics of both waves and particles, depending on the experimental context:\n\n1. Wave-like properties:\n- Exhibits wave interference\n- Has wavelength and frequency\n- Demonstrates diffraction patterns\n- Follows wave equations\n\n2. Particle-like properties:\n- Carries discrete quantum of energy\n- Travels at a specific momentum\n- Interacts with matter in discrete units\n- Detected as individual \"packets\" of energy\n\n3. Quantum Mechanical Description:\n- Described by quantum wave functions\n- Probabilistic behavior\n- Exhibits quantum superposition\n- Can be mathematically represented as both wave and particle\n\n4. Experimental Evidence:\n- Double-slit experiment demonstrates dual nature\n- Photoelectric effect shows particle-like interactions\n- Interference patterns reveal wave characteristics\n\n5. Modern Understanding:\n- Not strictly a particle or wave\n- A quantum entity with properties transcending classical definitions\n- Best described by quantum field theory\n\nThis dual nature is fundamental to modern quantum physics and challenges classical physics' traditional categorizations of matter and energy.",
